t Wagner did, said, and wrote, drawing from abundant material already well known but also from less familiar sources, including hitherto seldom discussed letters and diaries and previously unpublished musical sketches. At the same time, Deathridge suggests that a true estimation of Wagner does not lie in an all too easy condemnation of his many provocative actions and ideas. Rather, it is to be found in the questions about the modern world and our place in it posed by the best of his stage works, among them Tristan und Isolde and Der Ring des Nibelungen. Controversy about Wagner is unlikely to go away, but rather than taking the line of least resistance by regarding him blandly as a "classic" in the Western art tradition, Deathridge suggests that we need to confront the debates that have raged about him and reach beyond them, toward a fresh and engaging assessment of what he ultimately achieved.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aOperay19th century. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Opera.2bisacsh  aclassical music.  acontroversial composer.  adeathridge.  ader ring des nibelungen.  aengaging assessment.  afamous classical composers.  amusic appreciation.  amusic history.  aperforming arts.  aprovocative actions.  atristan and isolde.  aunderstanding wagner.  aunpublished musical sketches.  awagner.  awestern art tradition.  awestern music canon.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025453440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093461040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520934610423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520934610/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyte